Principal Component Analysis

Dataset happy

This dataset contains 157 individuals and 10 variables, 1 quantitative variable is considered as illustrative, 1 qualitative variable is considered as illustrative.

1. Study of the outliers

The analysis of the graphs does not detect any outlier.

2. Inertia distribution

The inertia of the first dimensions shows if there are strong relationships between variables and suggests the number of dimensions that should be studied.

The first two dimensions of PCA express 65.58% of the total dataset inertia ; that means that 65.58% of the individuals (or variables) cloud total variability is explained by the plane. This percentage is relatively high and thus the first plane well represents the data variability. This value is strongly greater than the reference value that equals 33.97%, the variability explained by this plane is thus highly significant (the reference value is the 0.95-quantile of the inertia percentages distribution obtained by simulating 774 data tables of equivalent size on the basis of a normal distribution).

From these observations, it should be better to also interpret the dimensions greater or equal to the third one.

Figure 2 - Decomposition of the total inertia on the components of the PCA

An estimation of the right number of axis to interpret suggests to restrict the analysis to the description of the first 2 axis. These axis present an amount of inertia greater than those obtained by the 0.95-quantile of random distributions (65.58% against 33.97%). This observation suggests that only these axis are carrying a real information. As a consequence, the description will stand to these axis.

3. Description of the plane 1:2

Figure 3.1 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction.

The Wilks test p-value indicates which variable factors are the best separated on the plane (i.e. which one explain the best the distance between individuals).

##       Region 
## 1.217174e-38

There only is one possible qualitative variable to illustrate the distance between individuals : Region.

Figure 3.2 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction. The individuals are coloured after their category for the variable Region.

Figure 3.3 - Variables factor map (PCA) The variables in black are considered as active whereas those in blue are illustrative. The labeled variables are those the best shown on the plane.

Figure 3.4 - Qualitative factor map (PCA) The labeled factors are those the best shown on the plane.

The dimension 1 opposes individuals such as New Zealand, Lithuania, Switzerland, Denmark and Greece (to the right of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals such as Burundi, Myanmar, Somaliland Region and Rwanda (to the left of the graph, characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis).

The group in which the individuals Lithuania and Greece stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables Dystopia.Resid, Life.Expectancy, Economy, Happiness.Score and Family (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variables Generosity, Happiness.Rank and Gov.Trust (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The group in which the individuals New Zealand, Switzerland and Denmark stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables Gov.Trust, Happiness.Score, Freedom, Economy, Life.Expectancy, Family and Generosity (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable Happiness.Rank.

The group in which the individuals Burundi, Myanmar, Somaliland Region and Rwanda stand (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variable Happiness.Rank.
  • low values for the variables Happiness.Score, Economy, Life.Expectancy, Family, Dystopia.Resid, Freedom and Gov.Trust (variables are sorted from the weakest).

Note that the variables Happiness.Score, Happiness.Rank and Western Europe are highly correlated with this dimension (respective correlation of 0.91, 0.9, 0.97). These variables could therefore summarize themselve the dimension 1.

The dimension 2 opposes individuals such as New Zealand, Burundi, Switzerland, Denmark, Myanmar, Somaliland Region and Rwanda (to the top of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals such as Lithuania and Greece (to the bottom of the graph, characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis).

The group in which the individuals Burundi, Myanmar, Somaliland Region and Rwanda stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variable Happiness.Rank.
  • low values for the variables Happiness.Score, Economy, Life.Expectancy, Family, Dystopia.Resid, Freedom and Gov.Trust (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The group in which the individuals New Zealand, Switzerland and Denmark stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables Gov.Trust, Happiness.Score, Freedom, Economy, Life.Expectancy, Family and Generosity (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable Happiness.Rank.

The group in which the individuals Lithuania and Greece stand (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables Dystopia.Resid, Life.Expectancy, Economy, Happiness.Score and Family (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variables Generosity, Happiness.Rank and Gov.Trust (variables are sorted from the weakest).

4. Classification

Figure 4 - Ascending Hierarchical Classification of the individuals. The classification made on individuals reveals 3 clusters.

The cluster 1 is made of individuals such as Somaliland Region, Myanmar, Rwanda and Burundi. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variable Happiness.Rank.
  • low values for the variables Life.Expectancy, Happiness.Score, Economy, Family, Freedom and Dystopia.Resid (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The cluster 2 is made of individuals such as Lithuania and Greece. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables Life.Expectancy, Economy, Family, Happiness.Score and Dystopia.Resid (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variables Gov.Trust, Happiness.Rank and Generosity (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The cluster 3 is made of individuals such as Denmark, Switzerland and New Zealand. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables Gov.Trust, Happiness.Score, Freedom, Economy, Life.Expectancy, Generosity and Family (variables are sorted from the strongest).
  • low values for the variable Happiness.Rank.
